Challenge: Add an aria-current Test for the Homepage

03
On this page
  1. 🛠 Solution: Test & Implement aria-current
    1. Writing the Test
    2. Adding aria-current Functionality

In the MegaNav, there’s a CampSpots logo link in the header that always links back to the homepage.

If a screen reader user is on the homepage and they focus on the logo in the header, it would be nice to let them know they are currently on the page that link goes to.

As discussed in the Semantics & ARIA Workshop, the aria-current property is meant exactly for this purpose.

Your challenge is to add a test to HomePage.test.js that checks for an aria-current property on the logo link.

The test will fail, so you will then have to implement the fix to make it pass.

This test-driven development (TDD) process is an excellent practice to adopt in your own work.

If you get stuck, reference the aria-current lessons from the Semantics & ARIA workshop or check the answer directory for a solution.

🛠 Solution: Test & Implement aria-current

Writing the Test

Inside of HomePage.test.js I’ll add a new it() block with a description of “should have an aria-current home link” along with the arrow function.

I’ll use the '#header-logo a' selector to get the logo link, and I’ll assert that it should have the aria-current attribute with a value of page.

Here’s what the test looks like all together:

it('should have an aria-current home link', () => {
        cy.get('#header-logo a').should('have.attr', 'aria-current', 'page')
    })
it('should have an aria-current home link', () => {
        cy.get('#header-logo a').should('have.attr', 'aria-current', 'page')
    })

Running Cypress, the UI will show us the test result fails as expected.

Adding aria-current Functionality

There are a few things to do inside of header.js where the logo link lives.

Because the Header exists across the entire site, we need to add a check to see if the user is on the homepage.

To do this, we’ll need some help from useState and useEffect, which we will import from React.

Create a currentPathName variable that we’ll use with the useState hook. Its initial value will be set to null.

const [currentPathname, setCurrentPathname] = useState(null)
const [currentPathname, setCurrentPathname] = useState(null)

Then using useEffect we can set the current pathname to document.location.pathname.

useEffect(() => {
		setCurrentPathname(document.location.pathname);
},[])
useEffect(() => {
		setCurrentPathname(document.location.pathname);
},[])

Now on the <a> tag that wraps around the logo, we can add the aria-current attribute.

If the current path is /, the user is on the homepage. This means that the value of aria-current should be set to page. Otherwise, we’ll make it null for now.

We can use a ternary for this logic:

aria-current={currentPathname === "/" ? "page" : null}
aria-current={currentPathname === "/" ? "page" : null}

Here’s an overview of the changes we made:

import React, { useEffect, useState } from "react";
...

const Header = ({ inert }) => {
	const [currentPathname, setCurrentPathname] = useState(null);

	useEffect(() => {
		setCurrentPathname(document.location.pathname);
	}, []);
	return (
		<header id="header" inert={inert}>
			<div id="header-nav">
				<div id="header-logo">
					<a
						aria-current={currentPathname === "/" ? "page" : null}
						href="/"
						className="header-main-item"
					>
					...
import React, { useEffect, useState } from "react";
...

const Header = ({ inert }) => {
	const [currentPathname, setCurrentPathname] = useState(null);

	useEffect(() => {
		setCurrentPathname(document.location.pathname);
	}, []);
	return (
		<header id="header" inert={inert}>
			<div id="header-nav">
				<div id="header-logo">
					<a
						aria-current={currentPathname === "/" ? "page" : null}
						href="/"
						className="header-main-item"
					>
					...

When Cypress runs the test again, we see that our test has passed.

Now when a screen reader user focuses on the logo when they are on the homepage, they will know that they are being linked to the page they are already on.
